\begin{abstract}
Clinical AI systems are overwhelmingly benchmarked in English, yet over a billion-plus speakers of Indian languages rely on healthcare systems where consultations occur in diverse regional languages. We study whether current open-source LLMs can generate
trustworthy English clinical summaries directly from multilingual doctor-patient dialogues, a practically important setting that has received almost no systematic attention. We evaluate two 7B-parameter LLMs (Mistral-7B and Qwen2.5-7B) across ten typologically diverse Indian languages under four settings: zero-shot prompting, few-shot prompting ($k{=}1$), translation of
source dialogues to English prior to summarization, and LoRA-based supervised fine-tuning.

We find that few-shot prompting unexpectedly \emph{degrades} performance in 8 of 10 language pairs; translation helps Indo-Aryan languages but harms Dravidian languages, revealing a strong typological divide; and clinical safety remains a major concern, with scores consistently below 3.0/5.0 across all conditions. Supervised fine-tuning substantially improves performance, eliminating cross-lingual disparities and reducing hallucination rates from $\sim$42\% to $\sim$10\%. We additionally conduct systematic qualitative case analyses across all ten languages, providing a clinical error taxonomy that characterizes failure modes by method and language family. 
