\section{Introduction}
Accurate and timely documentation of clinical encounters is a cornerstone of modern healthcare systems. Clinical consultations between doctors and patients typically has a rich mix of essential details - including symptoms, diagnostic reasoning, medication histories, treatment decisions, and relevant psycho-social context; all of which are vital for accurate documentation and continuity of care, yet much of this content is never reliably captured in structured clinical records. In India alone, primary healthcare workers conduct hundreds of millions of consultations annually across a population that speaks 22 constitutionally scheduled languages spanning four major language families \citep{gala2023indictrans2}.
The cognitive burden of manual documentation
in this setting is substantial, and errors of omission in clinical notes are well-documented as a leading source of adverse patient outcomes \citep{clusmann2023future}.

Automatic summarization of clinical dialogues using Large Language Models (LLMs) offers a promising path toward reducing this burden. Recent work has demonstrated that instruction-tuned LLMs achieve competitive performance on English clinical summarization benchmarks ~\citep{tang2023gersteinlab,
abacha2023overview}. However, the overwhelming majority of clinical NLP research targets high-resource languages-most often English-leaving a vast multilingual clinical documentation need unaddressed. Real-world clinical communication spans diverse languages, and healthcare delivery frequently occurs in multilingual and low-resource linguistic environments. For Indian languages, which range from relatively well-resourced Indo-Aryan languages such as Hindi and Bengali to morphologically complex languages like Marathi, and script-distinct Dravidian languages such as Telugu, Tamil, and Kannada, existing LLM-based
summarization pipelines are entirely unevaluated.

In this paper, we conduct a systematic investigation of the trustworthiness of LLM-based clinical summarization across
\textbf{ten typologically diverse Indian languages} as shown in Table\ref{tab:language_data}. The languages span five script families, two major typological groupings (Indo-Aryan and Dravidian), and a spectrum of NLP resource availability from high (English, Hindi) to severely low (Dogri, Assamese). We analyze the trustworthiness of cross-lingual clinical summarization systems, focusing on trustworthiness, safety, and explainability. We examine how linguistic and resource differences influence summarization quality and demonstrate that performance degrades substantially for low-resource languages. To the best of our knowledge, this is the first systematic study that characterizes trustworthiness failures in multilingual clinical dialogue summarization for Indian languages. These results underscore the need for linguistically informed, safety-aware evaluation frameworks for multilingual clinical NLP. 
Our principal contributions are as follows:

\begin{itemize}
  \item We present the first comprehensive evaluation of open-source LLMs on clinical dialogue summarization across ten typologically diverse Indian languages, spanning multiple scripts, language families (Indo-Aryan and Dravidian), and resource levels.
  \item We propose a multi-dimensional evaluation framework that integrates traditional lexical metrics, LLM-as-a-judge scoring for trustworthiness aspects: truthfulness, safety, explainability, and clinical entity-level analysis.
  \item We benchmark four widely used strategies: zero-shot prompting, few-shot prompting, translate-then-summarize, and supervised fine-tuning, providing a unified comparison under a consistent experimental setup.
  \item We demonstrate a pronounced performance disparity across languages, revealing significant gaps not only in overall summarization quality but also in key trustworthiness attributes between high-resource and low-resource settings.
  
