\section{Task, Data, and Models}
\label{Task}

\subsection{Task Definition}

We study the problem of cross-lingual clinical dialogue summarization, where the input is a multi-turn doctor–patient conversation in an Indian language, and the output is a structured clinical summary in English, matching realistic deployment contexts where medical records are maintained in English while consultations occur in the patient's native language.

\subsection{Dataset}

We use data from the Shared Task on Patient-Centric Clinical Dialogue Summarization\footnote{\url{https://www.codabench.org/competitions/10527/}}, The corpus comprises train/validation/test splits of carefully annotated clinical encounters. The dialogues exhibit high linguistic complexity: lengths vary dramatically (ranging from 4,000 to over 7,000 tokens per encounter), and natural code-switching with English medical terminology is highly prevalent across all regional languages. Table~\ref{tab:language_data} describes the language properties.

