We identify three mechanisms. First, \textit{template lock}: the demonstration summary encodes a particular clinical narrative structure, and the model adheres to it even when the test dialogue contains content that falls outside that structure. Omission rates increase in 14 of 20 language-model combinations under few-shot.
Second, \textit{entity bleed}: entities from the demonstration dialogues-patient demographics, medication names, symptom descriptions migrate into the generated summary for a different patient. This inflates hallucination counts with content that is clinically real but belongs to the wrong case, making the error invisible to surface-level metrics. Third, \textit{calibration
disruption}: for models already well-calibrated to clinical summarization at zero-shot, the demonstration introduces a competing prior that interferes with generation. The English zero-shot condition illustrates this clearly; Mistral-English F1 drops from 0.652 to 0.558 under few-shot, the largest degradation is in the Mistral few-shot condition, and precisely where the model is best calibrated.

These observations are consistent with prior work showing that demonstrations primarily encode format rather than semantic content~\citep{workrethinking}, and that few-shot biases can actively hurt performance compared to zero-shot when the model's prior is already reasonable~\citep{zhao2021calibrate}. There are
two exceptions: Qwen-Gujarati (F1 $+0.134$) and Mistral-Telugu (F1 $+0.096$). Both have the highest zero-shot hallucination rates in their respective matrices (0.693 and 0.718), few-shot is beneficial only when zero-shot generation is bad, otherwise it introduces more noise than signal.

One observation worth noting is that ROUGE-L and BERTScore are nearly insensitive to the zero-shot/few-shot difference ($\Delta < 0.012$), while entity-level metrics show meaningful changes. This is a concrete reminder that surface overlap metrics should not be the primary
evaluation criterion in clinical settings, where the cost of a fabricated drug name or missed diagnosis far exceeds the cost of slightly different phrasing.

