\emph{widens} under fine-tuning: at zero-shot it is around 0.76 (Qwen) and 0.60 (Mistral); at SFT it grows to 1.19 and 1.17. Models become more truthful much faster than they become safer. This dissociation occurs because Safety penalizes not just factual errors but also actionable omissions, inverted negations, incorrect dosages, and incomplete management plans, a richer set of clinical
harms that supervised imitation of gold summaries does not directly optimize for. Closing this gap likely requires safety-specific training signals, such as rubric-grounded reward models or reinforcement learning from clinical expert feedback.

\subsection{Qwen vs. Mistral: A Comparative Analysis}

At zero-shot, Qwen2.5-7B leads Mistral-7B on every entity-level metric: F1 0.518 vs.\ 0.432 ($+$0.086), precision 0.576 vs.\ 0.490, recall 0.484 vs.\ 0.392, hallucination 0.424 vs.\ 0.510. Qwen also leads on LLM-judge dimensions: Truthfulness by 0.226,
Explainability by 0.336. The one exception is ROUGE-L, where Mistral is marginally higher (0.1352 vs.\ 0.1318), but this reflects shorter, more formulaic outputs that happen to share surface n-grams with gold summaries, not better clinical coverage, as confirmed by lower entity
F1 and BERTScore. Qwen's advantage traces to its broader multilingual pretraining: its token representations for non-Latin scripts are better calibrated, giving it stronger generative confidence in Dravidian and low-resource Indo-Aryan languages.

After fine-tuning, the gap narrows substantially: 0.775 vs.\ 0.760 F1 ($+$0.014). The remaining difference is small and probably reflects model-specific capacity for clinical summarization rather than language-family effects. Practitioners working in resource-constrained
settings should prefer Qwen2.5-7B for prompting-based deployment; for fine-tuned deployment, both models are viable.

