The gap is widest under SFT, not narrowest. Standard fine-tuning on gold summaries teaches the model to produce accurate-sounding content, improving Truthfulness and Explainability, but does not sufficiently optimize for the absence of dangerous omissions or clinical distortions. Safety evaluation by an expert judge penalizes subtle failures that do not show up in n-gram comparison against a gold reference, such as an inverted negation (``no dysphagia'' becoming ``mild dysphagia'') or a conditional plan (``consider biopsy if laryngoscopy is abnormal'') becoming a definitive recommendation (``biopsy is required''). These errors survive fine-tuning unless the training objective specifically targets them.

The safety deficit is also not uniformly distributed across
