\section{Human Evaluation}
\label{sec: human_eval}
To validate our automated LLM-as-a-judge evaluation , we conducted a human study across four languages: \textit{Tamil}, \textit{Kannada}, \textit{Marathi}, and \textit{Hindi}. For each language annotators evaluated zero-shot and few-shot summaries using the same three dimensional rubric as our LLM judge: Truthfullness, Safety, and Explainability, plus an overall trust rating. Table \ref{tab:human_eval_examples} presents a representative sample of these human evaluations for Marathi (Indo-Aryan) and Tamil (Dravidian) across the Zero-Shot and Few-Shot paradigms. The human annotations corroborate our automated findings: while Few-Shot prompting often improves the superficial flow and formatting of the summary (higher Explainability), it actively introduces severe clinical hallucinations (e.g., fabricating geographic locations like "Pune") and degrades factual Truthfulness.

\section{Clinical Error Taxonomy}
\label{sec: CET}
To complement the quantitative results, we conducted systematic qualitative analysis across all ten languages, examining generated summaries against source dialogues and gold reference summaries. We identified eight recurring error mechanisms, which we organize into the Clinical Error Taxonomy presented in Table~\ref{tab:error_taxonomy}. Examples are shown in Table~\ref{tab:case_a} and Table~\ref{tab:case_b} present in Section~\ref{sec:appendix}.

